A unique future
JERUSALEM – With my now almost 90 years of age, I cannot recall a time when the past was so irrelevant for political decision-making.
No significant development of the present has been predicted by anyone beforehand.
Experts studied the past, but due to their entrapment in old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of the world today, in which events are more interdependent than ever before in a scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, we cannot predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation that cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and their leaders is diminishing. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy concerns all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome, because science and technology are boundless.
Global operating companies want to follow their business worldwide, thereby on the one hand causing a loss of sovereignty, but on the other hand weakening racism and prejudices as well as, to a significant extent, nationalism.
Due to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically skilled than their parents and are connected to each other through social networks that overcome national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark not a clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
The younger generation knows that the way states and economies are currently being led is unsuitable for the new era.
Yet there are political "free-riders" who want to exploit this latest awakening. However, not by developing an agenda of freedom, but by introducing new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, mainly Islamist extremists take the protests of the youth generation for themselves and thereby steal the revolution from them.
Israel has positively reacted to the will of the young generation, but it cannot and should not interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are at the heart of the rebellious youth and their legitimate longing for freedom and basic rights, which are supposed to enable them to have their voices heard, to choose their political leadership, and to secure their livelihood.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, because the existence as an island of prosperity in the midst of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
Yet there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists are trying to gain control over less well-organized Liberals in elections, thereby preventing peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current societal upheavals threaten their way of life, which also includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of traditional authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example to others in achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, for its success is based on the fact that the country had absolutely nothing at the beginning.
When we returned to our homeland, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could rely solely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. For this reason, we currently have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita in the world.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We use less water and yet achieve higher crop yields per square meter of farmland than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also accomplish.
We are willing to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Foremost, we must do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and this is not Israel's purpose.
We genuinely support the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
Für uns ist Frieden sowohl ein moralischer Imperativ als auch eine nationale Sicherheitsstrategie, denn die Lösung des Konflikts würde helfen, die Region durch Neutralisierung der Extremisten zu stabilisieren, die darauf aus sind, die Bürgerbewegungen zu manipulieren, um ihre radikale Agenda voranzutreiben.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to those countries that seek freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and pioneering political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Particularly, Iran is a source of moral corruption, where extremism is promoted and reforms are blocked. They crush legitimate protests of their own citizens and work against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
In addition, Iran uses multiple proxies to incite terrorism against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, in Lebanon, and in Iraq.
If Iran acquires nuclear weapons, its leaders could shake the Near and Middle East and incite even more extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But not only Israel is threatened. Iran is a danger to peace and stability around the world.
The democracies of the world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it is no longer possible.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have a duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children for dealing with the world of today.
Zu einer Zeit, da die Vergangenheit für die Prognose der Zukunft irrelevant geworden ist, muss Bildung allen Kindern die Möglichkeit bieten, ihr Potenzial auszuschöpfen.
The teachers of today should motivate our children towards creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free speech
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back has no meaning.
